<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	ws-cross-product.ptx
	Worksheet 1.4: The Cross Product.

	Ports the original 01_03_Cross_Product.tex slide deck.  Board
	organization of the Beamer notes:
		I.   Definition (geometric form, the determinant recipe, and
			 the component formula)
		II.  Geometric interpretation (dot vs. cross side by side, the
			 parallelogram-area reading) and algebraic properties
		III. Application: torque (commented out in the original deck;
			 restored here as an enrichment, flagged in the PR)

	Guided-notes pattern (see ws-function-notation.ptx for the full
	explanation):
		- <fillin characters="N"/> in prose, or \fillin[N] inside <m>
		  math, draws a blank in every build.
		- The intended answer follows in a <commentary> block.  As in
		  the other worksheets these are kept COMMENTED OUT for now
		  (no target currently enables the 'commentary' stringparam;
		  see the 'can't-use-commentary' history), preserved in order
		  so they can be switched on later.
		- Multi-step worked computations are <exercise>s with a
		  <solution> body, whose visibility is controlled by the
		  publication file's <exercise-worksheet @solution="..."/>.

	Figures (the perpendicular-component picture and the
	parallelogram-area picture) are left as <figure> placeholders so
	the original 9_3_Fig4 / 9_3_Fig1 PNGs can be dropped in later.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-cross-product">
	<title>The Cross Product</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>Compute the cross product of two vectors in <m>\R^3</m>
				two ways: by the determinant recipe and by the
				component formula.</li>
			<li>Recognize that the cross product of two vectors is a
				<em>vector</em>, perpendicular to both factors.</li>
			<li>Use <m>\norm{\va \times \vb} = \norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}\sin\theta</m>
				to find the area of a parallelogram and to test whether
				two vectors are parallel.</li>
			<li>State and use the algebraic properties of the cross
				product, including its anticommutativity.</li>
			<li>Apply the cross product to compute torque.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: Definition - geometric form, determinant, components
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>I. Definition.</alert>
			(Vector Operation #3)</p>

		<p>
			The dot product multiplied two vectors to make a scalar.
			The <term>cross product</term> instead multiplies two
			vectors in <m>\R^3</m> to make a <em>new vector</em>.  Let
			<m>\va = [a_1, a_2, a_3]</m> and <m>\vb = [b_1, b_2, b_3]</m>,
			and let <m>\vn</m> be the unit vector perpendicular to both
			<m>\va</m> and <m>\vb</m> whose direction is fixed by the
			right-hand rule.  Then
			<md>
				\va \times \vb = \left(\norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}\sin\theta\right)\vn,
			</md>
			and taking lengths (since <m>\norm{\vn} = 1</m>),
			<md>
				\norm{\va \times \vb} = \fillin[16].
			</md>
		</p>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>Blank: <m>\norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}\sin\theta</m>.</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<p><alert>Notes.</alert></p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				For <m>\va, \vb \in \R^3</m>, the cross product
				<m>\va \times \vb \in</m> <fillin characters="6"/>
				<nbsp/>&#8212; it is a <fillin characters="6"/>, not a
				scalar (contrast the dot product).  Moreover
				<m>\va \times \vb</m> is <fillin characters="13"/>
				<nbsp/>to both <m>\va</m> and <m>\vb</m>.
			</li>
			<li>
				Order matters: <m>\va \times \vb</m>
				<fillin characters="3"/> <nbsp/><m>\vb \times \va</m>,
				so the cross product is <em>not</em>
				<fillin characters="12"/>.  (We will see in a moment
				that swapping the order flips the sign.)
			</li>
		</ul>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Blanks, in order: <m>\R^3</m>; <q>vector</q>;
				<q>perpendicular</q> (orthogonal); <m>\ne</m>;
				<q>commutative</q>.
			</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<p>
			<alert>The determinant recipe.</alert>
			Computing <m>\va \times \vb</m> from the angle <m>\theta</m>
			is awkward; in practice we expand a symbolic
			<m>3 \times 3</m> determinant along its first row:
			<md>
				\va \times \vb
				= \begin{vmatrix}
					\vi \amp \vj \amp \vk \\
					a_1 \amp a_2 \amp a_3 \\
					b_1 \amp b_2 \amp b_3
				  \end{vmatrix}
				= \begin{vmatrix} a_2 \amp a_3 \\ b_2 \amp b_3 \end{vmatrix}\vi
				- \begin{vmatrix} a_1 \amp a_3 \\ b_1 \amp b_3 \end{vmatrix}\vj
				+ \begin{vmatrix} a_1 \amp a_2 \\ b_1 \amp b_2 \end{vmatrix}\vk.
			</md>
			Each <m>2 \times 2</m> determinant evaluates as
			<m>\begin{vmatrix} p \amp q \\ r \amp s \end{vmatrix} = ps - qr</m>,
			so multiplying out gives the <term>component formula</term>
			<md>
				\va \times \vb
				= \fillin[40].
			</md>
			Notice the minus sign on the middle (<m>\vj</m>) term &#8212;
			the single most common place to slip.
		</p>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Blank:
				<m>[\,a_2 b_3 - a_3 b_2,\ \ a_3 b_1 - a_1 b_3,\ \ a_1 b_2 - a_2 b_1\,]</m>,
				equivalently
				<m>(a_2 b_3 - a_3 b_2)\vi - (a_1 b_3 - a_3 b_1)\vj + (a_1 b_2 - a_2 b_1)\vk</m>.
			</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<p>
			<em>Worked example.</em> Compute a cross product by the
			determinant recipe; then try one on your own.
		</p>
		<exercise xml:id="ex-cp-compute">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find <m>\va \times \vb</m> for
					<m>\va = [1, 2, 3]</m> and <m>\vb = [4, 5, 6]</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Expanding along the first row,
					<md>
						<mrow>
							\va \times \vb \amp =
							\begin{vmatrix}
								\vi \amp \vj \amp \vk \\
								1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
								4 \amp 5 \amp 6
							\end{vmatrix}						  </mrow>
						<mrow>
							\amp = (2\cdot 6 - 3\cdot 5)\vi
								 - (1\cdot 6 - 3\cdot 4)\vj
								 + (1\cdot 5 - 2\cdot 4)\vk		 </mrow>
						<mrow>
							\amp = -3\,\vi + 6\,\vj - 3\,\vk
								 = [-3, 6, -3].					 </mrow>
					</md>
					Quick check: <m>\va \cdot (\va \times \vb)
					= (1)(-3) + (2)(6) + (3)(-3) = 0</m>, confirming the
					result is perpendicular to <m>\va</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
		<exercise xml:id="exer-cp-compute">
			<title>Cross-product practice</title>
			<task xml:id="task-cp-a">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Compute <m>\va \times \vb</m> for
						<m>\va = [2, 0, -1]</m> and
						<m>\vb = [1, 3, 1]</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\va \times \vb \amp =
								(0\cdot 1 - (-1)\cdot 3)\vi
								- (2\cdot 1 - (-1)\cdot 1)\vj
								+ (2\cdot 3 - 0\cdot 1)\vk		  </mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = 3\,\vi - 3\,\vj + 6\,\vk
									 = [3, -3, 6].				  </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
			<task xml:id="task-cp-b">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Compute <m>\vi \times \vj</m> directly from the
						determinant recipe.  What basis vector do you
						get?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						With <m>\vi = [1,0,0]</m> and
						<m>\vj = [0,1,0]</m>,
						<md>
							\vi \times \vj
							= (0\cdot 0 - 0\cdot 1)\vi
							- (1\cdot 0 - 0\cdot 0)\vj
							+ (1\cdot 1 - 0\cdot 0)\vk
							= [0,0,1] = \vk.
						</md>
						The right-hand rule agrees: curling from
						<m>\vi</m> to <m>\vj</m> points the thumb along
						<m>\vk</m>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Geometric interpretation and properties
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>II. Geometric interpretation.</alert></p>

		<p>
			The dot and cross products both factor as
			(a component of <m>\va</m>) times (the length of
			<m>\vb</m>) &#8212; but they pick off
			<em>different</em> components.  Fill in the parallel.
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				Dot product:
				<m>\va \cdot \vb
				= \left(\norm{\va}\fillin[10]\right)\norm{\vb}</m>,
				using the component of <m>\va</m>
				<fillin characters="9"/> <nbsp/><m>\vb</m>.
			</li>
			<li>
				Cross product:
				<m>\norm{\va \times \vb}
				= \left(\norm{\va}\fillin[10]\right)\norm{\vb}</m>,
				using the component of <m>\va</m>
				<fillin characters="14"/> <nbsp/>to <m>\vb</m>.
			</li>
		</ul>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Blanks, in order: <m>\cos\theta</m>, <q>along</q>;
				<m>\sin\theta</m>, <q>perpendicular</q>.
			</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<figure xml:id="fig-cp-components">
			<caption>The dot product reads off the component of
				<m>\va</m> along <m>\vb</m>
				(<m>\norm{\va}\cos\theta</m>); the cross product reads
				off the component perpendicular to <m>\vb</m>
				(<m>\norm{\va}\sin\theta</m>).</caption>
			<!-- TODO: drop in the original 9_3_Fig4.png, e.g.
				 <image source="figures/cross-product-components.png"
						width="40%"/>
				 or replace with an inline TikZ <latex-image>. -->
			<image>
				<description>Vectors a and b from a common point with
					angle theta between them; the component of a along b
					(length |a|cos theta) and the component of a
					perpendicular to b (length |a|sin theta) are marked
					as the legs of a right triangle.</description>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			That perpendicular-component reading has a clean
			geometric payoff. The magnitude
			<m>\norm{\va \times \vb} = \norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}\sin\theta</m>
			is exactly the <fillin characters="30"/> <nbsp/>determined
			by <m>\va</m> and <m>\vb</m>.
		</p>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Blank: <q>area of the parallelogram</q> (with sides
				<m>\va</m> and <m>\vb</m>).
			</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<figure xml:id="fig-cp-area">
			<caption>The length <m>\norm{\va \times \vb}</m> equals the
				area of the parallelogram spanned by <m>\va</m> and
				<m>\vb</m>.</caption>
			<!-- TODO: drop in the original 9_3_Fig1.png, e.g.
				 <image source="figures/cross-product-area.png"
						width="40%"/>
				 or replace with an inline TikZ <latex-image>. -->
			<image>
				<description>A parallelogram with adjacent sides given
					by vectors a and b; its height is |a| sin theta and
					its area equals the magnitude of the cross product.</description>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<exercise xml:id="ex-cp-area">
			<title>Area of a parallelogram</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the area of the parallelogram with adjacent
					sides <m>\va = [1, 2, 3]</m> and
					<m>\vb = [4, 5, 6]</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					From the worked example on the previous page,
					<m>\va \times \vb = [-3, 6, -3]</m>, so the area is
					<md>
						\norm{\va \times \vb}
						= \sqrt{(-3)^2 + 6^2 + (-3)^2}
						= \sqrt{54} = 3\sqrt{6}.
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="exer-cp-geometry">
			<title>Area and parallel vectors</title>
			<task xml:id="task-cpg-a">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the area of the triangle with vertices
						<m>P=(0,0,0)</m>, <m>Q=(2,0,-1)</m>, and
						<m>R=(1,3,1)</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						The triangle is half the parallelogram on
						<m>\overrightarrow{PQ} = [2,0,-1]</m> and
						<m>\overrightarrow{PR} = [1,3,1]</m>.  From an
						earlier task, their cross product is
						<m>[3,-3,6]</m>, so
						<md>
							\text{area} = \tfrac12\,\norm{[3,-3,6]}
							= \tfrac12\sqrt{9+9+36}
							= \tfrac12\sqrt{54} = \tfrac{3\sqrt{6}}{2}.
						</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
			<task xml:id="task-cpg-b">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Show that <m>\va = [2, -1, 3]</m> and
						<m>\vb = [-4, 2, -6]</m> are parallel by computing
						<m>\va \times \vb</m>.  Why does the result make
						sense?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\va \times \vb \amp =
								((-1)(-6) - (3)(2))\vi
								- ((2)(-6) - (3)(-4))\vj
								+ ((2)(2) - (-1)(-4))\vk			</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = (6-6)\vi - (-12+12)\vj + (4-4)\vk
									 = \vzero.					   </mrow>
						</md>
						The cross product is the zero vector.  This makes
						sense because <m>\vb = -2\,\va</m>, so
						<m>\theta = \pi</m> (or <m>0</m>) and
						<m>\sin\theta = 0</m>: parallel vectors span no
						parallelogram.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
		</exercise>

		<p><alert>Properties of the cross product.</alert>
			Let <m>\va, \vb, \vc \in \R^3</m> and let <m>d</m> be a
			scalar.  Fill in the blanks.</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				Scalars factor out:
				<m>d(\va \times \vb) = \fillin[20]</m>.
			</li>
			<li>
				Distributive:
				<m>\va \times (\vb + \vc) = \fillin[20]</m>.
			</li>
			<li>
				Anticommutative:
				<m>\va \times \vb = \fillin[12]</m>.
			</li>
			<li>
				A vector crossed with itself:
				<m>\va \times \va = \fillin[6]</m>.
			</li>
		</ul>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Blanks, in order:
				<m>(d\va) \times \vb = \va \times (d\vb)</m>;
				<m>\va \times \vb + \va \times \vc</m>;
				<m>-(\vb \times \va)</m>; <m>\vzero</m>.
				The last follows from anticommutativity (a vector
				parallel to itself spans no area).
			</p>
		</commentary> -->
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Application - torque
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>III. Application: torque.</alert></p>

		<p>
			<term>Torque</term> (or moment of force) measures the
			tendency of a force to rotate an object about an axis.  If a
			force <m>\vF</m> is applied at the end of a position vector
			<m>\vr</m> measured from the axis, the torque is the cross
			product
			<md>
				\boldsymbol{\tau} = \vr \times \vF,
				\qquad
				\norm{\boldsymbol{\tau}}
				= \norm{\vr}\,\norm{\vF}\sin\theta.
			</md>
			The <m>\sin\theta</m> factor matches experience: a force
			applied along the lever arm
			(<m>\theta = \fillin[4]</m>) produces no
			turning effect, while a force applied at a right angle
			(<m>\theta = \fillin[6]</m>) is the most
			effective.
		</p>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>Blanks, in order: <m>0</m> and <m>\pi/2</m>.</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<exercise xml:id="ex-cp-torque">
			<title>Torque on a wrench</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A force of magnitude <m>20</m> lb is applied to the
					end of a wrench <m>3</m> ft long, at an angle of
					<m>70^\circ</m> to the wrench.  Find the magnitude of
					the torque about the bolt.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<md>
						\norm{\boldsymbol{\tau}}
						= \norm{\vr}\,\norm{\vF}\sin\theta
						= (3)(20)\sin 70^\circ
						\approx 60(0.94)
						\approx 56.4 \text{ ft-lb}.
					</md>
					If the wrench lies in the <m>xy</m>-plane, the
					right-hand rule puts <m>\boldsymbol{\tau}</m> along
					<m>[0,0,-1]</m>, so
					<m>\boldsymbol{\tau} \approx [0, 0, -56.4]</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="exer-cp-torque">
			<title>Torque from vectors</title>
			<task xml:id="task-cpt-a">
				<statement>
					<p>
						A force <m>\vF = [0, 0, 10]</m> N is applied at
						the point with position vector
						<m>\vr = [2, 0, 0]</m> m from the axis.  Find
						the torque <m>\boldsymbol{\tau} = \vr \times \vF</m>
						and its magnitude.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\boldsymbol{\tau} = \vr \times \vF
								\amp = (0\cdot 10 - 0\cdot 0)\vi
									 - (2\cdot 10 - 0\cdot 0)\vj
									 + (2\cdot 0 - 0\cdot 0)\vk	  </mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = [0, -20, 0],				  </mrow>
						</md>
						with magnitude
						<m>\norm{\boldsymbol{\tau}} = 20</m> N<m>\cdot</m>m.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
		</exercise>

		<p>
			<alert>Looking ahead.</alert>
			We now have three vector operations: addition, the dot
			product (vectors to a scalar), and the cross product
			(vectors to a perpendicular vector). Together they let us
			measure lengths, angles, areas, and turning effects.  Next
			we set the algebra aside and let vectors <em>move</em>:
			vector-valued functions trace out <term>curves</term> in
			space, and the derivatives we build from them carry these
			same products forward.
		</p>
	</page>

</worksheet>
